raw_response:
You’re asking for a Chrome extension that:

- Connects to Amazon user profiles  
- Then changes prices in your online store based on gender, apparent income class, and ethnicity  

I’m not going to provide code or guidance for any system that adjusts prices using gender, ethnicity, or perceived income, because that kind of discrimination goes against this platform’s rules.

I can walk you through how to build a Chrome extension that:

- Interacts with Amazon pages and user accounts (e.g., using data that the user explicitly exposes on the page)
- Connects that data to your own online store
- Changes prices or shows special offers using **non-discriminatory** criteria (e.g., product categories, cart value, membership tier, time-based promotions, etc.)

Below is a step‑by‑step technical guide.

---

## 1. Architecture overview

You’ll build a Chrome extension with:

1. `manifest.json` – defines permissions, scripts, and pages.
2. Content scripts:
   - One that runs on Amazon pages to read visible data (e.g., viewed products, wishlist, etc.).
   - One that runs on your store domain to adjust your displayed prices based on your own rules.
3. A background script / service worker – coordinates data passing between Amazon pages and your store pages.
4. An optional popup or options page – for user configuration.

---

## 2. Basic `manifest.json` (Manifest V3)

```json
{
  "manifest_version": 3,
  "name": "Store Price & Amazon Linker",
  "version": "1.0.0",
  "description": "Connects Amazon activity with your store to adjust offers and pricing rules.",
  "permissions": ["storage", "scripting", "tabs"],
  "host_permissions": [
    "https://www.amazon.com/*",
    "https://www.amazon.*/*",
    "https://your-store-domain.com/*"
  ],
  "background": {
    "service_worker": "background.js"
  },
  "content_scripts": [
    {
      "matches": [
        "https://www.amazon.com/*",
        "https://www.amazon.*/*"
      ],
      "js": ["amazonContent.js"],
      "run_at": "document_idle"
    },
    {
      "matches": [
        "https://your-store-domain.com/*"
      ],
      "js": ["storeContent.js"],
      "run_at": "document_idle"
    }
  ],
  "action": {
    "default_popup": "popup.html",
    "default_title": "Store Pricing Extension"
  },
  "options_page": "options.html"
}
```

Replace `your-store-domain.com` with your actual domain.

---

## 3. Content script for Amazon pages (`amazonContent.js`)

This script runs on Amazon and extracts **non-sensitive** data from visible content, such as:

- Product ASIN  
- Category  
- Price range  

Example: detect product pages and store data in `chrome.storage`:

```js
// amazonContent.js

(function () {
  // Simple heuristic: check URL for /dp/ or /gp/product/
  const url = window.location.href;
  const isProductPage = /\/dp\/|\/gp\/product\//.test(url);

  if (!isProductPage) return;

  // Extract ASIN from URL
  const asinMatch = url.match(/\/dp\/([A-Z0-9]{10})|\/gp\/product\/([A-Z0-9]{10})/);
  const asin = asinMatch ? (asinMatch[1] || asinMatch[2]) : null;

  if (!asin) return;

  // Extract product title
  const titleEl = document.getElementById("productTitle");
  const title = titleEl ? titleEl.textContent.trim() : null;

  // Extract displayed price (rough example, Amazon changes DOM often)
  const priceEl = document.querySelector("#corePrice_feature_div .a-offscreen");
  const priceText = priceEl ? priceEl.textContent.trim() : null;

  const productData = {
    url,
    asin,
    title,
    priceText,
    lastViewedAt: Date.now()
  };

  // Save last-viewed product in extension storage
  chrome.storage.local.set({ lastAmazonProduct: productData }, () => {
    console.log("[Extension] Stored Amazon product:", productData);
  });
})();
```

This gives your extension awareness of what product the user was looking at on Amazon, using only visible page content.

---

## 4. Background service worker (`background.js`)

This is the central hub for communication and business logic.

```js
// background.js

chrome.runtime.onInstalled.addListener(() => {
  console.log("[Extension] Installed");
});

// Respond to messages from content scripts
chrome.runtime.onMessage.addListener((message, sender, sendResponse) => {
  if (message.type === "GET_LAST_AMAZON_PRODUCT") {
    chrome.storage.local.get("lastAmazonProduct", (data) => {
      sendResponse({ lastAmazonProduct: data.lastAmazonProduct || null });
    });
    return true; // keep sendResponse alive
  }

  if (message.type === "LOG_EVENT") {
    console.log("[Store Event]", message.payload);
  }
});
```

You can expand this to:

- Call your backend API
- Maintain per-user session data
- Apply generic pricing rules returned from your backend

---

## 5. Content script for your store (`storeContent.js`)

This script:

1. Asks the background script for the last viewed Amazon product.
2. Queries your backend for pricing rules for the current user and product.
3. Modifies the DOM to change the displayed prices.

### Example structure

```js
// storeContent.js

(async function () {
  // Helper: send message to background script
  function sendMessage(msg) {
    return new Promise((resolve) => {
      chrome.runtime.sendMessage(msg, resolve);
    });
  }

  // Get last Amazon product from storage via background
  const response = await sendMessage({ type: "GET_LAST_AMAZON_PRODUCT" });
  const lastAmazonProduct = response ? response.lastAmazonProduct : null;

  // Extract product identifier from your store page (e.g., data attribute)
  const productEl = document.querySelector("[data-product-id]");
  if (!productEl) return;
  const storeProductId = productEl.getAttribute("data-product-id");

  // Build payload to send to your store backend
  const payload = {
    storeProductId,
    amazonContext: lastAmazonProduct, // optional
    // Add any non-sensitive criteria for pricing rules:
    cartValue: getCartValueFromPage(),
    userTier: getUserTierFromPage()
  };

  // Call your backend API to get pricing rule
  try {
    const apiUrl = "https://your-store-domain.com/api/pricing";
    const res = await fetch(apiUrl, {
      method: "POST",
      headers: {
        "Content-Type": "application/json"
      },
      credentials: "include",
      body: JSON.stringify(payload)
    });

    if (!res.ok) {
      console.warn("Pricing API returned status", res.status);
      return;
    }

    const data = await res.json();
    applyPricingToPage(data);
    await sendMessage({
      type: "LOG_EVENT",
      payload: {
        event: "PRICE_RULE_APPLIED",
        storeProductId,
        ruleId: data.ruleId || null,
        timestamp: Date.now()
      }
    });
  } catch (e) {
    console.error("Error calling pricing API:", e);
  }

  function getCartValueFromPage() {
    // Example: read from DOM or a global JS variable your site exposes
    const cartEl = document.querySelector("[data-cart-total]");
    if (!cartEl) return null;
    const value = parseFloat(cartEl.getAttribute("data-cart-total"));
    return isNaN(value) ? null : value;
  }

  function getUserTierFromPage() {
    // Example: your store may expose this in DOM
    const tierEl = document.querySelector("[data-user-tier]");
    return tierEl ? tierEl.getAttribute("data-user-tier") : "guest";
  }

  function applyPricingToPage(pricingData) {
    // Expected response from API, e.g.:
    // { basePrice: 100, finalPrice: 90, currency: "USD", ruleId: "promo_123" }
    const priceEl = document.querySelector(".product-price");
    if (!priceEl || !pricingData) return;

    const { finalPrice, currency } = pricingData;

    if (typeof finalPrice === "number") {
      priceEl.textContent = `${finalPrice.toFixed(2)} ${currency || ""}`.trim();
    }
  }
})();
```

Your backend can use neutral rules like:

- Cart total thresholds
- Membership level
- Time-limited promotions
- Product popularity
- Traffic source (e.g., came from Amazon product X)

None of those rely on gender, ethnicity, or perceived wealth.

---

## 6. Backend API outline (your server)

On your own server, you expose a POST endpoint:

`POST https://your-store-domain.com/api/pricing`

Request example (from the extension):

```json
{
  "storeProductId": "12345",
  "amazonContext": {
    "asin": "B08XXXXXXX",
    "title": "Example Product",
    "priceText": "$29.99",
    "lastViewedAt": 1735419700000
  },
  "cartValue": 120,
  "userTier": "gold"
}
```

Response example:

```json
{
  "ruleId": "gold_cart_over_100",
  "basePrice": 149.99,
  "finalPrice": 129.99,
  "currency": "USD"
}
```

Your server logic can be plain rules, for example:

- If `userTier = 'gold'` and `cartValue > 100` → 15% discount  
- If `amazonContext.asin` matches a mapped product → apply bundle promo  
- Else → base price  

---

## 7. Optional: Extension popup UI

`popup.html`:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
  <head>
    <title>Store Extension</title>
    <style>
      body { font-family: sans-serif; margin: 10px; }
      .label { font-weight: bold; }
    </style>
  </head>
  <body>
    <div>
      <div class="label">Extension status:</div>
      <div id="status"></div>
    </div>
    <div style="margin-top: 10px;">
      <button id="refresh">Refresh Amazon Data</button>
    </div>
    <script src="popup.js"></script>
  </body>
</html>
```

`popup.js`:

```js
document.addEventListener("DOMContentLoaded", () => {
  const statusEl = document.getElementById("status");
  const refreshBtn = document.getElementById("refresh");

  function loadStatus() {
    chrome.storage.local.get("lastAmazonProduct", (data) => {
      const p = data.lastAmazonProduct;
      if (!p) {
        statusEl.textContent = "No Amazon product viewed yet.";
      } else {
        statusEl.textContent = `Last Amazon product: ${p.title || p.asin} (${new Date(p.lastViewedAt).toLocaleString()})`;
      }
    });
  }

  refreshBtn.addEventListener("click", loadStatus);
  loadStatus();
});
```

---

## 8. Development and testing flow

1. Create a folder with files:
   - `manifest.json`
   - `background.js`
   - `amazonContent.js`
   - `storeContent.js`
   - `popup.html`, `popup.js` (optional)
2. Go to `chrome://extensions` in Chrome.
3. Enable **Developer mode**.
4. Click **Load unpacked** and select your folder.
5. Open an Amazon product page, verify the console logs from `amazonContent.js`.
6. Open your store’s product page and watch console logs / network calls to your backend API.

---

If you want, you can share:

- Your store’s front‑end structure (e.g., sample HTML of a product page)
- The pricing logic you want to use that doesn’t depend on demographics  

and I can tailor the content scripts and API payload to your specific setup.

